column4: Four of the 14 member board are appointed by the University. The Chancellor appoints one and the remaining three are appointed by the Vice Chancellors.

The Faculty Club at the University of California San Diego (UCSD) is physically located on the UCSD campus with long term lease from the University. The club was founded in 1988 to provide a place in a central location for colleagues and community to socialize and intellectualize over food in a casual atmosphere of UCSD. Membership in the club is required for participation and is limited to faculty, staff and graduate students as well and retired employees, community members with an interest in the educational and intellectual life of the campus, persons at other select non-profit research institutions, Chancellors Associates and select businesses adding to the educational and intellectual life of the campus (must be approved by 2/3 vote of the board), and campus departments. Luncheon meals are served weekdays and periodic special events scheduled.

Without the Faculty Club no single space of sufficient size would be available regularly nor meals served. The casual atmosphere and central location of the club serves as a focal point for university employees and supporters. It allows formal and informal gatherings of university colleagues and a meeting place for activities. Some of these activities would continue on an ad hoc basis in the absence of the club but the club was established to facilitate these interactions.

Housetop Center administers Catherine of Siena Virtual College. The amounts indicated in line 10 represent tuition paid for women and men enrolled for courses with our college. Catherine of Siena Virtual College is an international educational enterprise working to empower women for life and leadership through transformative women's and gender studies. Our inter- disciplinary courses promote gender equity, as well as, international and inter-cultural understanding and respect. We combine the best Information Communications Technology (ICT) with a student-focused pedagogical practice that takes seriously the way authentic, transformative learning occurs. We create small interactively engaged communities where students find the safety and support they need to examine issues that are important to their lives, strengthening their skills and confidence and enhancing their leadership potential for creating positive change in the world. On 01 July 2014, the content of our courses and the administration of the college were handed over to Roehampton University. The University was chosen for its dedication to empowering women and men and for its willingness to take over the name and the functions of the online college. See catherinecollege.net for details.

column4: TREAS. REGS. SECTION 1.170A-9(F)(3)(I) PROVIDES THAT IN ORDER TO MEET THE "FACTS AND CIRCUMSTANCES" TEST, THE ORGANIZATION MUST NORMALLY RECEIVE SUBSTANTIAL SUPPORT (MORE THAN 10%) FROM GOVERNMENTAL CONTRIBUTION. INFORMATION INDICATES THAT COMPLETE COLLEGE HAS RECEIVED APPROXIMATELY 16.69% IN PUBLIC SUPPORT, SUBSTANTIALLY ABOVE THE 10% THRESHOLD. IN ADDITION TO THE 10% THRESHOLD TEST, TREAS. REGS. SECTION 1.170A-9(F)(3)(II) PROVIDES THAT THE ORGANIZATION MUST BE ORGANIZED AND OPERATED SO AS TO ATTRACT NEW AND ADDITIONAL PUBLIC OR GOVERNMENTAL SUPPORT ON A CONTINUOUS BASIS. AN ORGANIZATION WILL MEET THIS REQUIREMENT IF IT: - MAINTAINS A CONTINUOUS AND BONA FIDE PROGRAM FOR THE SOLICITATION OF FUNDS FROM THE GENERAL PUBLIC, OR - IT CARRIES ON ACTIVITIES DESIGNED TO ATTRACT SUPPORT FROM THE GOVERNMENT OR 509(A)(1) CHARITIES. COMPLETE COLLEGE SATISFIES BOTH TESTS. IT MAINTAINS A CONTINUOUS AND BONA FIDE PROGRAM FOR CHARITABLE CONTRIBUTIONS FROM THE PUBLIC AND CARRIES ON THE TYPE OF CHARITABLE ACTIVITIES THAT ARE DESIGNED TO ATTRACT SUPPORT FROM GOVERNMENTAL UNITS AND THE GENERAL PUBLIC AS IS EVIDENCED BY THE SIGNIFICANT STATE GOVERNMENT INVOLVEMENT WITH COMPLETE COLLEGE IN ITS "COMPLETION PROGRAM"

column4: THIS ORGANIZATION SUPPORTS THE METROPOLITAN ANDREY SHEPTYTSKY INSTITUTE OF EASTERN CHRISTIAN STUDIES ("MASI") WHICH IS LOCATED AT SAINT PAUL UNIVERSITY IN OTTAWA, ONTARIO, CANADA. THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATION, MASI, IS AN INSTITUTE AT THE UNIVERSITY OF SAINT PAUL. THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN THE ORGANIZATIONS IS HISTORICAL AND CONTINUING AS THE FOUNDATION HAS BEEN SUPPORTING THE INSTITUTE SINCE 1989. THE FOUNDATION'S PRIMARY FUNCTION IS TO DETERMINE ANNUALLY OR AS NEEDED THE AMOUNTS TO BE CONTRIBUTED TO THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATION.

THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATION ("MASI") HAS A CLOSE CONTINUOUS WORKING RELATIONSHIP WITH THE FOUNDATION. IT MAINTAINS A SIGNIFICANT VOICE BY WAY OF TWO KEY ORGANIZATIONAL MEMBERS, THE ACTING DIRECTOR OF MASI AND A FORMER PRESIDENT AND BOARD MEMBER. THESE INDIVIDUALS ARE INVOLVED IN BOTH ORGANIZATIONS' OPERATIONS AND DISCUSSIONS. IN ADDITION, THESE INDIVIDUALS PREPARE THE INSTUTUTE'S BUDGET WHICH IS REVIEWED, MODIFIED AND THEN APPROVED BY THE FOUNDATION'S BOARD. THE BUDGET IS THE BASIS FOR THE CONTRIBUTIONS GRANTED BY THE FOUNDATION TO MASI.
